How often have you and I, Sir George, pursued a Man who can think any thing, pitied the Condition of the few Men of Sense, who are sometimes among the Crowd of Beaux, who attend the Two Sister Beauties to all Places of polite Diversion in Town?
For those Ladies think it a mortal Injury done to those Ladies Charms, if the Men about those Ladies have Eyes or Ears for any Object but those Ladies Faces, or any Sound but that of those Ladies Voices: So that the Connoisseurs in Music, who attend those Ladies to Ranelagh, must stop those Ladies Ears, like Ulysses, when the Siren Frasi sings; and the Wits, who gallant those Ladies to the Side box, must lay a much greater Constraint upon those Ladies, in order to resist the Soul-moving Garrick; and appear insensible, while he is upon the Stage.
