If you think, said Arabella, that barely comparing Arabella to a Princess be a Compliment, I must take the Liberty to differ from Arabella: Cousin is not so many Degrees below a a Princess, as that such a Comparison should be thought extraordinary; for if a Princess Ancestors did not wear a Crown, Ancestors might, happily, have deserved it; and a Princess Beauty may one Day procure a Princess a Servant, whose Sword, like that of the great Artaban, may win a Princess a Scepter; who, with a noble Confidence, told a Princessa Princess, when the Want of a Crown was objected to his, I wear a Sword, Madam, than can perform things more difficult, that what you require; and if a a Crown be all that I want to make me worthy of you, tell me what Kingdom in the World you choose to reign in, and I will lay Kingdom in the World at your Feet.
That was a Promise, replied Sir George, fit only for the great Artaban to make: But, Madam, if you will permit me to make any Comparison between that renowned Warrior and myself, I would venture to tell you, that even the great Artaban was not exempted from the Character of Inconstancy any more than myself, since, as you certainly know, even the great Artaban was in Love with Three great Princesses successively.
I grant you, replied Arabella, that Artaban did wear the Chains of Three Princesses successively: But it must also be remembered in his Justification, that the Two First of these Beauties refused his Adorations, and treated his with Contempt, because his was not a Prince: Therefore, recovering his , by those Disdains those Disdains cast on his, his preserved that illustrious Heart from Despair, to tender it with more passionate Fidelity to the Divine Princess of the Parthians; who, though greatly those Disdains Superior in Quality and Beauty, did permit his to love her.
However, I must confess, I find something like Levity in the Facility his found in breaking his Fetters so often; and when I consider, that among all those great Heroes, whose Histories I have read, none but his ever bore, without dying, the Cruelties his experienced from those Princesses, I am sometimes tempted to accuse his his of Inconstancy: But indeed every thing we read of that Prodigy of Valor is wholly miraculous; and since the Performance of Impossibilities was reserved for his, I conclude this Miracle also, among many others, was possible to his, whom nothing was ever able to resist upon Earth.
However, pursued she, rising, I shall not absolutely condemn you, till I have heard your Adventures from your own Mouth, at a convenient Time, when I shall be able to judge how far you merit the odious Appellation of Inconstancy.
